<TMU|<tuple|1.1.0|2025.0.15>>

<style|<tuple|generic|number-europe>>

<\body>
  In RAG, this is the Hybrid Searching technic. It basically means using two statistical data to generate the vector to represent the importance of some words.

  \;

  TF-IDF(<with|font-series|bold|Term Frequency-Inverse Document Frequency>):

  Determine if a word is necessary in a paragraph. Since it doesn't relate to prob., it is a deterministic algorithm.

  \;

  <section|TF(Term Frequency)>

  <with|font-series|bold|>

  <\equation>
    TF<rsub|ij>=<frac|n<rsub|ij>|<big|sum><rsub|i>n<rsub|ij>>,
  </equation>

  where <math|n<rsub|ij>> represent the count of existence of term <math|t<rsub|i>> in the file <math|d<rsub|j>>. Then\ 

  <\equation>
    TF<rsub|ij>\<approx\>P<around*|(|A|)>,
  </equation>

  where A={Choose a word from <math|d<rsub|j>>,this word is <math|t<rsub|i>>} if you sample enough time.

  \;

  However, the problem is maybe some words appear many times but has nothing to do with the topic, like the charactor Jack in Titanic appears many times but has nothing to do with the story.

  That's why we need IDF.

  \;

  <section|IDF(Inverse Document Frequency)>

  <\equation>
    IDF<rsub|i>=log<around*|(|<frac|<around*|\||D|\|>|1+<around*|\||j:t<rsub|i>\<in\>d<rsub|j>|\|>>|)>,
  </equation>

  where <math|D\<assign\><around*|{|d<rsub|j>|}><rsub|j=1><rsup|\<infty\>>> represents all the files. And since we are analyzing some files, <math|<around*|\||D|\|> >will not be 0.

  And the more term <math|t<rsub|i>> exists in every file, the less IDF will be. If the term like “the” appears in every file, the IDF of “the” will be <math|log<around*|(|<frac|<around*|\||D|\|>|1+<around*|\||j:t<rsub|i>\<in\>d<rsub|j>|\|>>|)>=log<around*|(|<frac|<around*|\||D|\|>|1+<around*|\||D|\|>>|)>\<less\>0>. If appears in every file except one, the IDF is 0.\ 

  We can represented as:

  <\equation>
    <frac|<around*|\||D|\|>|1+<around*|\||j:t<rsub|i>\<in\>d<rsub|j>|\|>>\<approx\><frac|<around*|\||D|\|>|<around*|\||j:t<rsub|i>\<in\>d<rsub|j>|\|>>\<approx\>P<around*|(|B|)><rsup|-1>,
  </equation>

  where P(B):={The word propotion in all the files}.

  \;

  So the equation of TF-IDF is:

  <\equation>
    TF-IDF=<around*|(|IDF\<times\>TF|)>=<around*|(|（log<around*|(|<frac|<around*|\||D|\|>|1+<around*|\||j:t<rsub|i>\<in\>d<rsub|j>|\|>>|)>）\<cdot\>\<bbb-I\><rsup|T>*\<odot\><around*|(|<frac|n<rsub|ij>|<big|sum><rsub|i>n<rsub|ij>>|)>|)><rsub|i,j\<in\><around*|[|n|]>>,
  </equation>

  <math|\<odot\>> is the Hadamard Product.<math|（log<around*|(|<frac|<around*|\||D|\|>|1+<around*|\||j:t<rsub|i>\<in\>d<rsub|j>|\|>>|)>）\<cdot\>\<bbb-I\><rsup|T>> is for reproducing the vector size(<math|\<bbb-I\>>) times to form a matrix to do product legally.

  \;

  This is tricky for the result is actually a matrix not a vector.

  Word "python":

  \ - IDF("python") = log(3 / 2) = 0.176 \<leftarrow\> appears in 2 out of 3 docs (calculated ONCE)

  \ - TF("python", doc 0) = 1/3 = 0.333 \<leftarrow\> appears 1 time in doc 0\ 

  \ - TF("python", doc 1) = 0/3 = 0 \<leftarrow\> appears 0 times in doc 1\ 

  \ - TF("python", doc 2) = 1/2 = 0.5 \<leftarrow\> appears 1 time in doc 2

  <\remark>
    It's good to think this result as an entropy, cuz it is a cross-entropy compare if the words get the same importance in one file and all the files.
  </remark>

  \;

  <section|Implementation>

  Let's consider a small example:

  <\verbatim-code>
    texts = ["Python is great", "FastAPI is fast", "Python FastAPI"]

    <next-line>

    words = vectorizer.get_feature_names_out()

    vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer()

    tfidf_matrix = vectorizer.fit_transform(texts)
  </verbatim-code>

  For words:

  - Takes all text

  - Splits by spaces: "Python", "is", "great", "FastAPI", "is", "fast", "Python", "FastAPI"

  - Converts to lowercase: "python", "is", "great", "fastapi", "is", "fast", "python", "fastapi"

  - Gets unique words: "python", "is", "great", "fastapi", "fast"

  - Sorts alphabetically: <strong|['fastapi', 'fast', 'great', 'is', 'python']>

  \;

  <section*|What does tfidf_matrix contain?>

  <code|<\code*>
    tfidf_matrix.toarray() =

    \ 

    \;

    [

    \;

    \;

    \ \ [0. \ \ \ 0. \ \ \ 0.517 0.517 0.681] \ # Doc 0: "Python is great"

    \;

    \;

    \ \ [0.517 0.681 0. \ \ \ 0.517 0. \ \ ] \ # Doc 1: "FastAPI is fast"

    \;

    \;

    \ \ [0.605 0. \ \ \ 0. \ \ \ 0. \ \ \ 0.796] \ # Doc 2: "Python FastAPI"

    \;

    \;

    ]
  </code*>>

  <strong|Each row = one document> <strong|Each column = one word (in alphabetical order)>

  <strong|Reading the matrix:>

  <\itemize>
    <item>Row 0, Column 0 = 0.0 \<rightarrow\> "fastapi" NOT in Doc 0

    <item>Row 0, Column 2 = 0.517 \<rightarrow\> "great" IS in Doc 0 (importance 0.517)

    <item>Row 0, Column 4 = 0.681 \<rightarrow\> "python" IS in Doc 0 (importance 0.681)
  </itemize>

  Perfect! Let me explain this step-by-step using the example:

  <code|<\code*>
    texts = ["Python is great", "FastAPI is fast", "Python FastAPI"]

    \;
  </code*>>

  After <code*|tfidf_matrix = vectorizer.fit_transform(texts)>:

  <code|<\code*>
    tfidf_matrix =\ 

    [

    \ \ [0. \ \ \ 0. \ \ \ 0.517 0.517 0.681] \ # Doc 0: "Python is great"

    \ \ [0.517 0.681 0. \ \ \ 0.517 0. \ \ ] \ # Doc 1: "FastAPI is fast"

    \ \ [0.605 0. \ \ \ 0. \ \ \ 0. \ \ \ 0.796] \ # Doc 2: "Python FastAPI" (the query)

    ]

    \;
  </code*>>

  Split the question vector from the knowledge vector

  <code|<\code*>
    query_vector = tfidf_matrix[-1]

    # Result: [0.605 0. \ \ \ 0. \ \ \ 0. \ \ \ 0.796] \ \<leftarrow\> Last row (the query)

    \;

    doc_vectors = tfidf_matrix[:-1]

    # Result:\ 

    # [[0. \ \ \ 0. \ \ \ 0.517 0.517 0.681] \ \<leftarrow\> Doc 0

    # \ [0.517 0.681 0. \ \ \ 0.517 0. \ \ ]] \<leftarrow\> Doc 1

    \;
  </code*>>

  \;

  <code|<\code*>
    similarities = cosine_similarity(query_vector, doc_vectors)[0]

    # Compares query [0.605, 0, 0, 0, 0.796] with each document

    # Result: [0.876, 0.315]

    # \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \<uparrow\> \ \ \ \ \ \ \<uparrow\>

    # \ \ \ \ \ Doc 0 \ \ Doc 1

    \;
  </code*>>

  <strong|Meaning:>

  <\itemize>
    <item>Doc 0 similarity = <strong|0.876> (very similar! shares "python")

    <item>Doc 1 similarity = <strong|0.315> (less similar, shares "fastapi" only)
  </itemize>

  <subsection*| Sort by similarity and get top results>

  <code|<\code*>
    top_indices = np.argsort(similarities)[-top_k:][::-1]

    \;
  </code*>>

  Let's say <code*|top_k = 2>:

  <code|<\code*>
    similarities = [0.876, 0.315]

    np.argsort(similarities) = [1, 0] \ # indices sorted by value (lowest to highest)

    \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \<uparrow\> \ \<uparrow\>

    \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ 0.315 first, 0.876 second

    \;

    [-top_k:] = [-2:] = [1, 0] \ # take last 2 (highest values)

    \;

    [::-1] = [0, 1] \ # reverse to get highest first

    \;
  </code*>>

  <strong|Result: <code*|top_indices = [0, 1]>> (Doc 0 is most similar, Doc 1 second)

  <subsection*| Filter and return>

  <code|<\code*>
    return [knowledge_base[i] for i in top_indices if similarities[i] \<gtr\> 0.1]

    # Check each index:

    # \ \ i=0: similarities[0]=0.876 \<gtr\> 0.1 \<checkmark\> \<rightarrow\> include "Python is great"

    # \ \ i=1: similarities[1]=0.315 \<gtr\> 0.1 \<checkmark\> \<rightarrow\> include "FastAPI is fast"

    #\ 

    # Returns: ["Python is great", "FastAPI is fast"]

    \;
  </code*>>

  So at last, we get the word both appears a lot and important to context.
</body>

